INSERT INTO "th_note" VALUES(1,'no','June 18, 2013','How to set up Yandex.Disk',
'Yandex.Disk is a cloud data storage from Yandex, the leader in the Russian speaking internet.
It is a highly competitive service with the cheapest upgrade price and uncompromised privacy managment.',
'<p>
    As it turned out, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Snowden#NSA_surveillance_disclosures">NSA
    stores and automatically analyzes</a> all the [private] information from US based major IT companies.
</p>

<p>
    Unfortunately all the major cloud data storage providers, i.e. Dropbox, Google and Microsoft, are compromised.
    Those people, who cares about their privacy, should search for an alternative.
</p>

<p>
    Hopefully there is a very competitive alternative: <a href="http://disk.yandex.com"><img src="yd.png" class="logo">Yandex.Disk</a>.
    It is brought by the leader of Russian speaking internet, by <a href="http://yandex.com">Yandex</a>.
</p>

<p>
    Out of the box you would get <b>10 Gb of storage</b>, 24/7/365 availability and Win/Mac clients.
    If you are Windows or Apple user, all you need to do is to register at
    <a href="https://passport.yandex.com">Yandex</a> and <a href="https://disk.yandex.com">download</a>
    official client.
</p>

<p>
    If you are a Linux user then there is still a possibility to use Yandex.Disk.
    You could do it via WebDAV.
</p>

<p>
    Let us denote your login as Yandex.Name, password as Yandex.Password
    and directory you wanted to use for Yandex.Disk as Yandex.Disk.Directory.
    Following steps set up Yandex.Disk on your Ubuntu.
</p>

<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            Install <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Davfs2">davfs2</a> on your system.
        </p>
        <pre class="brush: bash">$ sudo apt-get install davfs2</pre>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p class="italic">N.B. skip this step if you want higher security.</p>
        <p>
            Add your account information into your secrets. Open it with you editor.
        </p>
        <pre class="brush: bash">$ sudo editor /etc/davfs2/secrets</pre>
        <p>Add next line to it:</p>
        <p class="mono">Yandex.Disk.Directory Yandex.Name Yandex.Password</p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Configure new file system record in fstab.
        </p>
        <pre class="brush: bash">$ sudo editor /etc/fastab</pre>
        <p>Add next line to it:</p>
        <p class="mono">https://webdav.yandex.ru:443 Yandex.Disk.Directory davfs noauto,user 0 0</p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>Let non-root users mount it.</p>
        <pre class="brush: bash">$ sudo dpkg-reconfigure davfs2</pre>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>Add yourself to the davfs2 group.</p>
        <pre class="brush: bash">$ sudo gpasswd -a User.Name davfs2</pre>
    </li>
</ol>

<hr/>

<p>You could simply mount your Yandex.Disk after these steps with</p>

<pre class="brush: bash">$ mount Yandex.Disk.Directory</pre>

<p>and unmount it with</p>

<pre class="brush: bash">$ umount Yandex.Disk.Directory</pre>
');
INSERT INTO "th_note" VALUES(2,'no','August 7, 2013','How to use Git Submodules',
'Git Submodules is essentially the neatest way to include
in your project third-party library or any git repository.',
'<p>
    There is a usual case when one need to incorporate into his project some other
    person work. If this work is not more than a couple of files, the straightforward
    way is possibly the best one.
</p>
<p>
    In the case when this work is stored as git repository and consists of a number of
    files then the best way is to use <a href="http://git-scm.com/book/en/Git-Tools-Submodules">git submodules</a>.
    It is like source-level equivalent of Debian package system, which has been proven to be extremely useful way
    to manage software, both for users and for developers.
</p>

<p>
    The typical use case is following. Suppose you have your git repository placed in directory A.
    Let the repository you want to incorporate be at git://some.url/of/repo.git and contains two folders: C, D and E,
    of which you are not interested in D.
    If you want to store this submodule at A/B path, then you could do the following actions.
</p>

<pre class="brush: bash">
$ cd A
$ git submodule add git://some.url/of/repo.git B
# with git version 1.8.4 or higher you could specify "--depth 1" for shallow submodules
$ cd B
$ git config core.sparsecheckout true # turning filtering on
$ echo C > ../.git/modules/B/info/sparse-checkout
$ echo D >> ../.git/modules/B/info/sparse-checkout
$ git read-tree -mu HEAD # applying filtering
</pre>

<p>
    Thats it. Once you need to change visible directories of submodule, just change submodule <i>sparse-checkout</i> file
    and repeat last command. Now you could manage your submodule state independently of you main repository.
</p>');
COMMIT;
